description.narrative:
In 2020, the UN Women Country Office continued to implement the country programme “Creating asafer world for women and girls in Mali”, the initial period of which (2016-2018) was extended to 2021. Thisreport, the fourth edition published by the UN Women Country Office in Mali, records the achievements of our agency and its partners in 2020. The programme contributed to the implementation of the Strategic Note 2014-2019 of the UN Women Country Office and has also contributed to its new Strategic Note 2020-2024 which is entirely aligned with the United Nations Sustainable Development Cooperation Framework (UNSDCF) 2020-2024. 
In 2020, the country programme and the annual work plan continued to focus on four areas of intervention. Some of the achievements in each area are detailed in the text that follows:
1-1) Women’s governance and political participation, aimed at strengthening women’s capacities to allow them to exercise effective leadership at all levels of decision-making
- The significant increase to 27.89% of women’s representation in the National Assembly (subsequentlydissolved) in the legislative elections of March/April 2020. UN Women contributed to the result through support for the widespread dissemination of the Electoral Act, Law No. 2018-14 (consolidated version of 28 February 2020) and the Gender Promotion Act, Law No. 2015-052, coaching of 100 women candidates (of whom 63 reached the second round and 32 were elected), and initiatives in favour of elections free of violence;
- Following the coup d’état leading to the dissolution of Parliament, women civil society leaders succeeded in contributing to the charter and roadmap of the transition and being represented 26.4% in the National Transition Council (CNT). To that end, UN Women provided its support for the creation of a Consortium of five networks of women’s organizations. Thus, women were able to adopt common positions around a joint agenda and engage in advocacy actions at high level with the national authorities and international bodies, such as the ECOWAS mediation, the African Union Commission and the United Nations System;
- Progress in terms of gender-responsive planning and budgeting (GRPB), notably with the availabilityof the “Gender report annexed to the Finance Act” produced by the Government with the support ofUN Women, the commitment by the Budget Monitoring Group to ensure greater accountability of local elected representatives and increased citizen control and review of the national GRPB strategy; 
- The launch of the master’s degree in Gender at the University of Bamako. For this collaboration between UN Women Mali and the University of Bamako concerning the launch of a master’s degree in Gender, courses started on 3 June 2020 with some 70 students divided into two groups. Most of the students are professionals in other sectors. In the framework of the support actions, the Office will facilitate the links between the University and the UN Women Gender Training Centre, in the framework of provision of human resources for the different modules;
- The elaboration of the strategic document with different ministries and the National Institute of Statistics of Mali (INSTAT) is an important part of the results. The document “Gender, women’s independence and implementation of the SDG and CREDD” was produced to draw attention to the implications of failure to consider gender financing in the Sustainable Development Goals (SDG) and the Strategic Framework for Sustanable Economic Development of Mali (CREDD). This document will also ensure better allocation of financial resources at national level.
1-2) Women’s economic independence, aimed at substantially reducing feminized poverty through entrepreneurship and agriculture, numeracy and extension of the public-private partnership
- The Women Business Centre (WBC), created in 2019, expanded its range of services to strengthenwomen’s resilience in the framework of management of their businesses. In 2020, 412 women increased their capacities to manage their businesses in the context of the health crisis thanks to the partnership with API(Agence pou rla Promotion des Investissements) in the framework of the IPAFE programme;
- Over 1,843 women, in 23 cooperatives, strengthened their resilience and that of their families in theface of the negative socioeconomic impacts of the pandemic, thanks to production capacities strengthened notably by the provision of production materials in the area of soap-making, dressmaking, cotton weaving, fish farming, market gardening and hiring; 
- In the area of "increased securitized access of women to cultivable land" and according to the land database for December 2020 prepared by UN Women:* 10 567 women organized in 118 groups acquired 332 ha of which 232 ha were secured by ownershipdeeds for 98 groups, or 8,495 members.* 3 horticultural areas of 7.5 ha improved in the Ségou and Kayes regions ensuring secured production.
- In the framework of mobilization of financial resources for agricultural production and marketing, credit of 36,350,000 FCFA was obtained by 4,603 women in agricultural production groups, thanks to financing through the partnership with the National Agricultural Development Bank (BNDA). Internal savings of the groups (“Saving for Change”) allowed granting of additional credits in the amount of 62,180,000 FCFA;
1-3) Elimination of violence against women and girls, aimed at creating a violence-free environment, notably thanks to an appropriate legal framework
- The establishment of 90 community mechanisms plus one National Coalition and three RegionalCoalitions of traditional community chiefs, religious leaders and human rights defenders in the Bamako, Kayes, Sikasso and Koulikoro regions;- Raising awareness of nurses and midwives on ways and means of humanizing care, improving itsquality and, above all, respecting the women’s and girls’ rights during childbirth. Childbirth has becomemore humanized; 
- Four platforms of young people engaged in the promotion of equality between the sexes, reproductivehealth, including the use of contraceptive methods and appropriation of the concept of family planningand elimination of GBV have been established and are in operation of the Ségou, Mopti, Timbukturegions and District of Bamako.- Continuation of the awareness raising and advocacy activities for the process of the adoption of thedraft law against GBV up to 2021
1-4) Women, peace and security, and humanitarian action, aimed at increasing women’s participation in the peace process and systematically integrating gender in humanitarian action
- The official launch of the third National Action Plan R1325 for the period 2019-2023 on 12 November 2020, which was marked by the signature of the Prime Minister for the first time, is an important decision of the Government of Mali. It shows political commitment to the implementation of the Women, Peace and Security agenda;
- Even if underrepresented in spaces for consultations and organs of the political transition, women civilsociety leaders succeeded on contributing to the charter and roadmap of the transition, and to achieve26.4% representation on the National Transition Council (CNT). With UN Women support, the creation ofa Consortium of five networks of women’s organizations allowed them to adopt common positions arounda joint agenda and engage in advocacy actions at high level with the national and international decision-makers, such as the ECOWAS mediation, the African Union Commission and the United Nations System.
- Women and girls affected by the conflicts, and their communities targeted by our interventions, haveincreased resilience thanks to higher incomes and savings, better access to credit and diversification of income-generating activities. Changes are also noted in terms of utilization of production practices better adapted to climate change; 
- In 2020, the Humanitarian Country Team (HCT) assumed a strong commitment to systematic and effective integration of gender in humanitarian actions in Mali with the adoption of the gender roadmap in humanitarian action. Thus, to respect the principle of “leave no one behind (LNOB)”, the direct humanitarian assistance provided by UN Women allowed 2,400 displaced persons, including 1,600 women in the Mopti and Ségou displaced persons camps, to use 400 household kits comprising personal hygiene items for women and girls.
* The UN Women Country Office also responded to the COVID-19 pandemic by contributing to the UnitedNations joint strategy in support of the Government of Mali, not only through actions aimed at prevention and protection against COVID-19, but also through COVID-19 impact studies with a gender perspective so as to better understand the distinct impact of COVID-19 on gender-based inequalities.
